----------- Comments for the authors -----------
Overall, the authors did a good job of developing a methodology to assess the state of the software development practices in research software. The authors mined research software repositories and interviewed domain experts to do so. However, there is some primary concern about the paper's motivation and presentation. 

- The Abstract lacks the motivation for the problem and the implications of the results. 
- The Introduction section could be a lot better. It should have described the problem and motivation behind the solution clearly. In addition, since there is no Background/Related work section, the introduction section should have discussed some of the related works more to provide a foundation of the study. 
- Some of the research questions are vague. For example, the authors talked about "current best practices" without spelling out or citing current best practices, "compare to research software in general," without providing the characteristics of research software in general. It was unclear what was going to be compared—similarly, tools and pain points of research software in general. The paper should specifically talk about all these points with proper citation. 
- The authors had a straightforward methodology to perform the study. 
- The presentation of the results and the mapping between the research questions and findings could have been presented better. For example, while the answers to the other RQs have their own section, RQ1 and RQ2 are blended with the methodology section. 
- RQ8 should have been specifically called out in section 7. It was mentioned in the introduction section but never called out after that.



