----------- Comments for the authors -----------
The paper describes an approach to evaluate the state of practice of domain specific research software in a generic way. Therewith an important step is done regarding the comparability of domains regading software development practices. The mix of repository mining and developer interviews is a great approach. Ideally, it could be used to also cross-check the assesment. For example, it is stated that some interviews suggested that CI is more commonly used as the analysis of the repository predicted, but it is not stated if this was used to adapt the existing assesment of the software. 
	Also mixing automated analysis with manual evaluation is a good approach. Since the required time for an assesment of a whole domain is still high, trying to introduce more automatic analysis tools should be a next step. 
	
	In total I think this paper is a very valuable contribution to the workshop and is a step in the right direction of research software analysis. 
	
	Despite all this praise, I discovered one flaw: In "Table 3 - Recommended artifacts in software development guidelines" at least for [16] the table is not correct. LICENSE, README, CONTRIBUTING, and CHANGELOG are required by the guideline as well. While the file names are not all stated explicitly, it is implicitly stated that these artifacts needs to be provided. README and CONTRIBUTING are even mentioned explicitly as possibile implementations for such artifacts.



